g.title: root
g.text: PHOTOSYNTHESIS

g.title: subtopic_0
g.text: INTRODUCTION TO PHOTOSYNTHESIS

g.title: subtopic_0_point_0
g.text: Photosynthesis is the process by which light energy is converted into chemical energy.

g.title: subtopic_0_point_1
g.text: Oxygenic photosynthesis produces oxygen as a byproduct.

g.title: subtopic_0_point_2
g.text: Anoxygenic photosynthesis uses different electron donors and does not produce oxygen.

g.title: subtopic_0_point_3
g.text: Photosynthesis is crucial for maintaining Earth's atmosphere and supporting life.

g.title: subtopic_0_point_4
g.text: Photoautotrophs synthesize food from CO2 and water, while photoheterotrophs use organic compounds.

g.title: subtopic_1
g.text: PHOTOSYNTHETIC MEMBRANES AND ORGANELLES

g.title: subtopic_1_point_0
g.text: Chloroplasts are the sites of photosynthesis in plants and algae.

g.title: subtopic_1_point_1
g.text: Thylakoids are membrane-bound compartments within chloroplasts where light-dependent reactions occur.

g.title: subtopic_1_point_2
g.text: Photosynthetic pigments like chlorophyll absorb light energy.

g.title: subtopic_1_point_3
g.text: Accessory pigments broaden the range of light absorbed.

g.title: subtopic_1_point_4
g.text: Bacteria embed photosynthetic proteins in their cell membranes or specialized structures.

g.title: subtopic_2
g.text: LIGHT-DEPENDENT REACTIONS

g.title: subtopic_2_point_0
g.text: Light absorption by chlorophyll initiates electron transport.

g.title: subtopic_2_point_1
g.text: Electron transport chain generates ATP through chemiosmosis.

g.title: subtopic_2_point_2
g.text: Water photolysis provides electrons and releases oxygen.

g.title: subtopic_2_point_3
g.text: NADPH is produced as a reducing agent.

g.title: subtopic_2_point_4
g.text: Z-scheme describes the electron flow in non-cyclic photophosphorylation.

g.title: subtopic_2_point_5
g.text: Cyclic photophosphorylation generates only ATP.

g.title: subtopic_3
g.text: LIGHT-INDEPENDENT REACTIONS (CALVIN CYCLE)

g.title: subtopic_3_point_0
g.text: RuBisCO catalyzes the fixation of CO2 into RuBP.

g.title: subtopic_3_point_1
g.text: ATP and NADPH from light-dependent reactions drive the cycle.

g.title: subtopic_3_point_2
g.text: Three-carbon sugars (G3P) are produced and used to synthesize glucose and other carbohydrates.

g.title: subtopic_3_point_3
g.text: Regeneration of RuBP ensures the cycle's continuation.

g.title: subtopic_3_point_4
g.text: Alternative carbon fixation pathways (C4 and CAM) enhance efficiency in specific environments.

g.title: subtopic_4
g.text: CARBON CONCENTRATING MECHANISMS

g.title: subtopic_4_point_0
g.text: C4 photosynthesis spatially separates CO2 fixation and the Calvin cycle.

g.title: subtopic_4_point_1
g.text: CAM photosynthesis temporally separates these processes.

g.title: subtopic_4_point_2
g.text: Carboxysomes in cyanobacteria concentrate CO2 around RuBisCO.

g.title: subtopic_4_point_3
g.text: Pyrenoids in algae perform a similar function.

g.title: subtopic_5
g.text: FACTORS AFFECTING PHOTOSYNTHESIS

g.title: subtopic_5_point_0
g.text: Light intensity, wavelength, and temperature affect photosynthetic rates.

g.title: subtopic_5_point_1
g.text: CO2 concentration influences the rate of carbon fixation and photorespiration.

g.title: subtopic_5_point_2
g.text: Water availability is crucial for maintaining turgor pressure and preventing stomatal closure.

g.title: subtopic_5_point_3
g.text: Nutrient availability impacts enzyme activity and pigment synthesis.

g.title: subtopic_6
g.text: EFFICIENCY AND EVOLUTION OF PHOTOSYNTHESIS

g.title: subtopic_6_point_0
g.text: Photosynthetic efficiency varies among organisms and is influenced by environmental factors.

g.title: subtopic_6_point_1
g.text: Early photosynthetic organisms likely used different electron donors than water.

g.title: subtopic_6_point_2
g.text: The endosymbiotic theory explains the origin of chloroplasts from cyanobacteria.

g.title: subtopic_6_point_3
g.text: Diverse eukaryotic lineages have evolved various photosynthetic mechanisms.

g.title: subtopic_6_point_4
g.text: Cyanobacteria played a key role in oxygenating Earth's atmosphere.
